In conclusion it will be worth while to put together what can be gathered frorn this letter respecting education in tlte provinces.

Schools oi two separate kinds were in existence, firsssy, government schools, not uncommon (⁴ multis in locis’); and secondly, schools established by public subscription where sufficient money could be raised to engage a teacher. They expected to be engaged (⁸ conduci') with acertaiupayment guaranteed. lf there was a good school in any place, boys came from a distance and took lodgings in the place to attend it.

Pliny's views set forth in this letter attest not only his generosity and interest in education, but a shrewd judgment in the matter quite on a level with modern opinion.
